**Requirements**

This project requires to build a light-weight tourism application for Canada, and it must be accessible through mobile devices and desktops. It enables the user to search for popular tourist destinations across Canada and view various tourist attractions in any desired destination. If a user wants to book a ticket, the application should allow to login with their account or to sign-up for registration. Once the payment is processed; a ticket is generated for the user. Also, the dashboard of the application should be displayed with analytics or reports which must be generated from the server-side application using the data from the database. The project requires the client applications to be lightweight with primary requirements which are as follows [CITATION Ala20 \l 16393].

- Security – The application should be secure and must not be vulnerable to attacks. To keep the application secure, the project requires to implement 2-factor authentication, and store encrypted data in the database.
- Accuracy – The project requires that the search response data and dashboard analytics be displayed accurately.
- Efficiency – The application should be efficient enough by being available for the users providing instant responses. To achieve this, the project requires to implement the load balancer to handle the incoming traffic and implement the auto-scaling functionality to upscale/downscale the resources.
- Responsiveness – To achieve this, the project requires the client applications to be thin and lightweight and work on the devices to accommodate as many users as possible.

Apart from the above-mentioned requirements, there are few functional requirements for this project which are listed below.

- Entire server-side functionalities must be implemented on the cloud by developing loosely coupled modules that must be tested individually before integration.
- The application must be designed using containerization. A dummy card 1111-1111-1111-1111 must be used for transactions and the application must perform validation during the payment process.

**Functionalities**

Below listed are the four functional modules in our application along with the list of functionalities that are implemented in each module.

## Login/Signup module:

- User registration
- User log in and log out
- SMS-based two-factor authentication
- Forgot password
- Display user profile
- Session management

## Search module

- Search attractions in a location

## Booking module

- Display buses for a selected origin of travel
- Book ticket by payment
- Generate ticket to the user
- Provide ticket history for logged in user

## Analytics module

- Display top searched places
- Display number of bookings for each location in last week

**Architecture**

The key requirement for this application was to allow users to simply search for a tourism location in Canada. Hence, we designed our cloud architecture focusing mainly on it.

Our tourism application comprises of four functional modules, Search, Booking, Login/Signup, and Analytics. We followed the microservices service-oriented architecture as shown in the below final design diagram where all the four modules are hosted in the cloud independent of each other. We designed loosely coupled modules in the microservices architectural style where each module is hosted in different AWS server interacting with MySQL database in its own Amazon RDS. The web and the mobile client applications connect to the various microservices running on the AWS cloud through REST APIs. The clients make HTTP requests to the services receive appropriate response in JSON format. All the services are hosted in separate docker containers on different EC2 instances of the AWS cloud. We ensured a high availability for our application by implementing load balancing and auto scaling mechanisms in ECS (Elastic Container Services) of AWS. Figure 1 illustrates how the API Gateway would act as an entry point to our services and handle API calls by interacting with these services. The architecture in implementation is explained in detail under the implementation section of this document.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Below is the list of AWS cloud services that we used in our project; and we explained the purpose of each cloud service briefly.

1. **AWS Cognito:** We used Cognito to perform user authentication functionalities such as login, sign up, forgot password, and SMS based two-step verification
2. **S3 Bucket:** We used the S3 bucket for two purposes, one is to store the image details and the other is to host our web application
3. **CloudFront:** We used CloudFront on top of S3 to reduce the latency in API responses by caching and to provide secure connection between client and server.
4. **RDS:** We used RDS instance to configure and connect the MySQL database. Each service has a separately configured RDS instance with necessary MySQL tables required for that service
5. **CloudWatch:** CloudWatch helped us to maintain logs for several AWS services that we used in our project. We used the logs to troubleshoot our application
6. **ECR:** We used ECR to save the docker images of our services. Each service has its own ECR repository with the docker image of that service.
7. **ECS:** We used ECS to run and deploy our containers from the images in ECR. Each cluster of ECS has a service with one EC2 instance and two docker containers running on that instance.
8. **Load balancer:** We used load balancer with the help of dynamic port mapping for distributing the load between the two containers
9. **Autoscaling group:** As the starter account does not support autoscaling of containers, we performed the auto scaling of the EC2 instance of our service in the ECS cluster. We scaled the instances to a maximum of 3 against the average instance CPU utilization of 50%
10. **API Gateway:** We used API Gateway as a single-entry point for our services. It serves approximately 10,000 API requests per second
11. **AWS CodeBuild:** We used CodeBuild for CI/CD of our services that gets triggered by a GitHub repository push event.

**Implementation**

We designed our application using MEAN stack technologies in which the angular client application makes API calls to the Amazon API Gateway that manages the RESTAPI calls exposed by the microservices. The microservices are developed in Node.js using Express framework.

## **Deployment**

For a given module in an AWS user account, we setup an RDS instance with MySQL database and loaded the data required for that module into that database. We set up the Node.js server application with a connection to the RDS instance and designed the APIs required for that module. Once the service is created with required APIs, we attached a Dockerfile in that application that helped us building an image for that service. We created a repository in the ECR (Elastic Container Repository) of the AWS account and pushed our docker image into it. We created a cluster in ECS by attaching it to a new security group and VPC and added an instance to the cluster. We created a load balancer in the AWS account to achieve a high availability for our application. A task definition is then created in the ECS by attaching the docker image of the service from the ECR. Once the task definition is ready with the mapped ports of the container, we created a service in the ECS and attached our container to the Application Load Balancer. We are using CloudWatch which helps us to monitor the logs of our services.

Once we have a set of APIs that are exposed by the load balancers for all the modules, we created a single-entry point for our APIs using the Amazon API Gateway by creating HTTP proxies for all our APIs. We used API Gateway to throttle requests in order to protect our microservices and to cache API responses, handle requests &amp; response transformation, and to reduce the operational complexity of creating and maintaining RESTful APIs. We used the APIs that are exposed from our API Gateway in our web and mobile client applications. In addition, we deployed our Angular client application to S3 bucket of AWS and configured AWS CloudFront on top of it to maintain secure connections.

For implementing the user management in the Login/Signup module, we used Amazon AWS Cognito to create and manage the users for our application. Amazon&#39;s Cognito service provides users authentication for our mobile and web applications. We created and configured a user pool for our application in the AWS Cognito based on our requirements such as choosing required attributes, authentication process etc. and we generated an application client to use in our client applications. We used the user pool id and the application client id in both the mobile and web applications to invoke the login and registration services. Cognito also helped us in configuring the two-factor authentication for our application. Once the users register to our application using the Registration page, they will receive a confirmation link to the registered email and only after confirming the account, we are storing the user details to the database. We also implemented SMS-based two-factor authentication when the user logins into the application by sending a verification code via SMS to the registered mobile number. Only after successful login, user will get access to the booking module. We used AWS Amplify library to integrate the Cognito services into our client applications. We also implemented the session management to our application such that users cannot visit the pages such as booking, payment gateway unless they are logged into the application. Also, we are retaining the current session even after the page refresh. Once the user logs into the application, we are fetching the user id of the logged in user from the database and using this id for further operations like booking. This way, we are handling the dependencies of our services in the microservice architecture.

We used S3 bucket to store the tourism attractions data that we are displaying in the search page of the application. We created a repository in the Amazon S3 to save the images of the attractions from all the locations of Canada and saved the image URLs to the MySQL database of RDS. We are accessing the data that is required to show in our search page from the database upon search of a location by the user.

**Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD)**

We performed CI/CD operations on our application services by using CodeBuild service of AWS. We created a build project for each service and configured it to perform these operations on that service. On every code change, our CI/CD operations include building the docker image, pushing it to ECR, stopping the running tasks/containers in ECS service, and rerun the containers of that service. We hooked up the build project with our GitHub repository on the PUSH event which means, every time a new push happens, the build process will start automatically. We wrote build specifications in a .yml of each service repository to perform the build process on each code commit. Below is the CodeBuild repository that we created for profile service of our application.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 5 CodeBuild project hooked up to our GitHub repository

The build specifications file that we wrote for each service contains pre-build, build, and post-build commands to perform the build process. Connecting to ECR repository, building the docker image, and pushing the new image to ECR is done in pre-build, build, and post-build phases, respectively. As our repository structure contains three directories of web, android, and server applications, to avoid this build process in unnecessary situations such as code commits in other repositories, we configured &quot;File\_path&quot; of CodeBuild project by providing the path of the desired service directory. This will make sure that only when there is a new code commit appears in profile service directory, build process of profile service will start to perform CI/CD operations on that service. Below is the screenshot that shows this configuration.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 6 Build project configured with file path

While these three operations serve the purpose of Continuous Integration (CI), to perform the Continuous Deployment (CD), we followed the below steps:

1. We built a new docker image with the same tag as previous images so there will not be a necessity to create a new task definition for our service.
2. Even though the new docker image contains the same tag, since the running tasks are in a steady state, they will not instantly use the new docker image and update their containers. So, to enforce the tasks to run new containers, we added an additional command in post-build phase of build process that serves this purpose. This command will make the running containers to be stopped, and reruns the containers using the new docker image. Below is the command that performs this CD operation.
